[4.7](https://github.com/airbnb/javascript#arrays--callback-return) Use return statements in array method callbacks.

`acc[index] = flatten;` makes no difference for the output in the second (good) example. Should this line be removed or am I missing something here?

This is currently in the docs. 
```js
// bad - no returned value means `acc` becomes undefined after the first iteration
[[0, 1], [2, 3], [4, 5]].reduce((acc, item, index) => {
  const flatten = acc.concat(item);
  acc[index] = flatten;
});

// good
[[0, 1], [2, 3], [4, 5]].reduce((acc, item, index) => {
  const flatten = acc.concat(item);
  acc[index] = flatten; 
  return flatten;
});
```

I am suggesting this:
```js
// better?
[[0, 1], [2, 3], [4, 5]].reduce((acc, item) => {
  const flatten = acc.concat(item);
  return flatten;
});
```

I can make a PR if you want.

Alignment recommendations for "Inline If with Logical && Operator"

This is different than React docs (https://reactjs.org/docs/conditional-rendering.html#inline-if-with-logical--operator).

```jsx
    // bad
    {showButton &&
      <Button />
    }

    // bad
    {
      showButton &&
        <Button />
    }

    // good
    {showButton && (
      <Button />
    )}

    // good
    {showButton && <Button />}
```

